0 @77752256@ NOTE1 CONT page 90 line 2091 CONT1 CONT 1911 deaths in the district of Lochee n the Burgh of Dundee1 CONT1 CONT Thomas Mooney, Jute Mill Worker (Married to Catherine Lynch)1 CONT1 CONT 1911 December Twenty Second 9h 45 m PM1 CONT 40 Whorterbank, Lochee1 CONT1 CONT M(ale) 49 years1 CONT1 CONT Mother Hannah Moooney, Jute Spinner (Deceased)1 CONT1 CONT Cause Alcohol Poisoning, 12h1 CONT1 CONT Informant Catherine Moonet her X mark, Widow (Present)1 CONT Registered 1911 December 28th at Lochee1 CONT1 CHAN2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 21:41:291 _CRE2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 21:35:370 @93848578@ NOTE1 CONT Before Sheriff Campbell Smith this afternoon, Thomas Mooney, labourer, Albert Street, Lochee, was charged with assaulting his wife. He denied the charge. Mrs Mooney stated her husband came home last Saturday night the worse for drink. She was in bed at th1 CONC e time and he siezed her by the hair of her head and pulled her onto the floor. He thereafter lifted a knife and drew it twice  across her throat, cutting her slightly. He also beat her with his fists and knocked her down. The Sheriff after hearing corrob1 CONC orative evidence, found the charge proved, and ordered prisoner to find caution of 30s to keep the peace for six months, or go prison lor twenty days. His Lordship remarked that if the knile had been sharp enough prisoner might have killed his wife.1 CONT1 CONT Published: Friday 20 December 18951 CONT Newspaper: Dundee Evening Telegraph1 CONT County: Angus, Scotland1 CONT Type: Article | Words: 133 | Page: 4 | Tags: none1 CHAN2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 22:21:021 _CRE2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 22:15:310 @64495943@ NOTE1 CONT Threatening to Cut His Wipe's Throat.— A labourer named Thomas Mooney, residing in Albert Street, Lochee, was charged before Sheriff Campbell Smith in Dundee Sheriff Court yesterday with wife assault. He pleaded not guilty. Mrs Mooney stated that she had 1 CONC been married sixteen years, and had had eleven of a family, seven of whom were alive. On Saturday, 14th inst., her husband came home the worse for drink. Sbe was in bed when he seized her by the hair of the of the head, pulled her upon the floor, and, rem1 CONC arking that he would cut her throat, he lifted a knife from the table and drew it twice acrces her neck, inflicting slight injuries. The accused also beat his wife with his fists, and knocked her down. His  Lordship found the chrge proved. He remarked tha1 CONC t if the knife had been sharp enough the accused might have killed his wife. In order that the prisoner migt have an opportunity of seeing whether anybody would put faith in the possibilities of his good behaviour for six months, his Lordship said he woul1 CONC d order him to find caution to the extent of 30s and failing that he would have to go to gaol for twenty days.1 CONT1 CONT Published: Saturday 21 December 18951 CONT Newspaper: Dundee Courier1 CONT County: Angus, Scotland1 CONT Type: Article | Words: 3234 | Page: 2 | Tags: none1 CONT1 CHAN2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 22:31:061 _CRE2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 22:24:570 @2733434@ NOTE1 CONT A Policeman Uses his Baton in Self Defence1 CONT1 CONT Alexander Dickson, policeman, was placed in the dock at Dundee yesterday afternoon.  Sheriff Campbell Smith charged with striking Mooney, fireman, Albert Lochee. and Alexander Grant, general dealer. Kerr's Lane, with baton at the junction of Coupar Angus 1 CONC and Liff Roads on  9th inst. He pleaded not guilty, and was defended al A. F. Burke. From the evidence for the prosecution it appeared that the policeman was in plain *clothes.  About the time of the alleged assault .Mooney and Grant were in public house 1 CONC  playing dominoes. Grant went out, and shortly afterwards Mooney also went into the street, a  third man told Mooney that Dickinson something to Grant. Mooney told the policeman if he came up the street he  would give him as much fighting wanted. Grant sa1 CONC id he went with them to see who was the better  man. When they got BIrkhill Road. Mooney said they had far enough. Dickson drew his baton and struck Mooney on the head and knocked him down. Grant went to Mooney' s assistance, and Dickson struck him on the1 CONC  face with the baton. In cross examination Mooney denied having said use a knife to Dickson if he had had one. For the defence James Fisher said he had observed Mooney and Grant  the accused, and threatening him. When they came to the corner of Coupar Ang1 CONC us and Liff Road  they sprang upon accused, who drew his baton in self-defence, and struck one of the men across the nose. They followed accused down Lidd Road, and one of them again attacked .When they came to High Street Mooney said "If I had had my jac1 CONC k knife in my pocket I would have cut his heart out". The accused was perfectly sober but Mooney and Grant were the worse for drink. Other witnesses corroborated. The Sheriff said he could not sav  in the circumstances that the accused  was not justified 1 CONC in using his baton in self-defence as far he  used it. The blows he  struck might have been enough for the purpose, but they not blows struck by man who meant to do  serious violence.  His Lordship should have preferred that he had knocked down his assail1 CONC ant, with his fists, but he did not think unnecessary violence had been used by the accused to himself and a man who did not use unnecessary violence to defend him self was quite justified.  He therefore found accused not guilty. 1 CHAN2 DATE 05 MAR 20223 TIME 12:47:311 _CRE2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 22:37:400 @14935676@ NOTE1 CONT Scotlands People1 CONT 1895 MOONEY, THOMAS (Prison registers, Reference HH21/47/6, PERTH PRISON (1846-1924)) Image 1561 CONT1 CONT 1 previous admission. 1 CONT Born Lochee, 1 CONT lives Lochee. 1 CONT Occupation Fireman. 1 CONT Roman Catholic. 1 CONT Good health. 1 CONT Assault and BP. 1 CONT Trial 20 December 1895, 1 CONT Sheriff Court, Perth. 1 CONT Convicted, 1 CONT incarcerated, 20 days or 30/- caution. 1 CONT Liberated 8 January 1896 Ex of 1 CONT Sen at Kinross.1 CHAN2 DATE 07 MAY 20253 TIME 19:36:011 _CRE2 DATE 07 MAY 20253 TIME 19:32:380 @94281140@ NOTE1 CONT Name:    Thomas Money / Moonie, 1 CONT Age:     6yrs 2mths,1 CONT Date:    2 June 18631 CONT Ref:     18151 CHAN2 DATE 07 FEB 20223 TIME 22:51:501 _CRE2 DATE 07 FEB 20223 TIME 22:51:480 @71440255@ NOTE1 CONT Thursday 29 January 18631 CONT Dundee Courier, page 21 CONT1 CONT Suicide.—Yesterday afternoon, & woman named Hannah Mooney, millworker, residing Liff Road, Lochee, attempted commit suicide by drinking a quantity of vitriol. It appears that after she left work at two o'clock, she purchased a small jug. and afterwards we1 CONC nt to the shop of Dr Munro, In High Street, where she purchased twopence worth of vitriol, the greater portion of which she drank on her way. 1 CHAN2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 21:28:341 _CRE2 DATE 22 FEB 20223 TIME 21:28:320 @6820866@ NOTE1 CONT 1863 Deaths in the district of Lochee, Burgh of Dundee in the county of Forfar1 CONT1 CONT Line 331 CONT1 CONT Hannah Mooney, Mill worker, single1 CONT 1863, February Eightyeenth1 CONT 8hrs 1m AM1 CONT Liff Road Lochee1 CONT Female, 30 years1 CONT Father: Michael Mooney, General Labourer1 CONT Mother Agnes Mooney MS Harrington1 CONT Suicide by vitreol, 3 weeks.1 CONT Informant James Mooney his X mark, Brother1 CONT Witness Jas Waddell, Registrar1 CONT Registered 1863 February 15th at Lochee1 CONT Jas Waddell, Registrar1 CHAN2 DATE 07 FEB 20223 TIME 23:09:101 _CRE2 DATE 07 FEB 20223 TIME 23:09:090 @51769280@ NOTE1 CONT Name:	Catherine Mc Donald1 CONT Gender:	Female1 CONT Birth Date:	25 Dec 18631 CONT Birth Place:	Dundee,Angus,Scotland1 CONT Father:	1 CONT Terence Mc Donald1 CONT Mother:	1 CONT Ann Guillan1 CHAN2 DATE 06 APR 20223 TIME 17:14:451 _CRE2 DATE 06 APR 20223 TIME 17:14:050 @52828512@ N